an class=title> ANIME AND JAPANESE</span><hr size=1> when i grow up i want to draw anime and make them on tv. the only thing that im not sure about is that if ill have to move to japan in order to do that. if so, i need help on the japanese language badly. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=maimaipanda>maimaipanda</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Resident Panda</span><br> <font color=#336699>(2/18/03 6:09:25 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1055.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.sit.wisc.edu/~mamiller2/temp/pandatea.jpg height=146 width=130></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: ANIME AND JAPANESE</span><hr size=1> well, i'm not an expert in the anime business or anything, but if you want to do straight up anime, chances are good that you'll have to work in japan.  I would imagine that the majority of the US animation industry is for giants like disney (which is not what i presume you mean by &quot;anime&quot;) or else computer animation firms like Pixar, etc.  Since you said &quot;draw anime and make them on tv&quot; i presume you're referring to the style of japanese animation like the series' shown on japanese tv (and occasionally in the US as well).  For this, you'll need to work out of Japan.  of course, anime is becoming increasingly popular in the US so by the time you're grown up, there may very well be stateside animation companies combining both western and japanese anime techniques.<br>
<br>
However (and you might want to ask on the photoshop/art forum or something) I would imagine that there is not a very high demand for foreign anime artists in japan, as there are more than enough highly skilled japanese to fill the available jobs.  Furthermore, japanese companies tend to be quite reluctant, on average, to hire foreigners when they could find a japanese individual to do the same task.  That having been said, i know that there *are* collaborations between japanese animation companies and western companies (for instance, to make the Final Fantasy movie) and often times game companies will send over american workers/animators etc. to work in their japan offices.  <br>
<br>
At any rate, if you want to move to Japan to pursue your dreams, more power to you!!  However, I'm not sure by what you mean when you say &quot;i need help on the japanese language badly&quot;.  Assuming you speak no japanese and are still rather young, my main advice would be: <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>START NOW...!!</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  the younger you start, the easier it will be.  Find a teacher (or if you're fortunate enough to live in a place where they teach it in school, take classes), try and audit university classes, find a conversation partner, get a good textbook (there are other threads in this forum about textbooks if you look hard enough), and above all <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>practice practice practice..!!</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->  you'll need to buckle down and go through the unpleasantry of memorizing the basic alphabets and grammer etc. before you can have enough of a base to start 'really' learning the language.  It's a long haul, but it's worth it in the end!  If you need more help, starnova started another thread in this forum about online resources for studying japanese.<br>
<br>
the fact that you're young right now (i'm presuming) is a huge advantage for you - it's so much easier to pick up foreign languages when you're younger.  You don't know how many times I wished I started studying japanese from when I was a little kid instead of from the university on!  *sigh* ah well.<br>
<br>
i assume you'll also need to brush up on your art skills like mad - but you'll need to refer to the other forums (photoshop/art questions most probably) to get the proper guidance for that aspect of your future career.<br>
<br>
